# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: nanoputian
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:nanoputian/1-2-diiodoethane] 1,2-Diiodoethane is most commonly used in organic synthesis in the preparation of samarium(II) iodide or ytterbium(II) iodide in an inert solvent such as THF.
[src:nanoputian/1-2-diiodoethane] In mass spectroscopy, 1,2-diiodoethane exhibits 5 major peaks, with the base peak showing at 155 m/z, which is the loss of one iodine atom (127 m/z).
[src:nanoputian/1-3-dioxolane] (+)-*cis*-Dioxolane is the trivial name for L-(+)-*cis*-2-methyl-4-trimethylammoniummethyl-1,3-dioxolane iodide which is a muscarinic acetylcholine receptor agonist.
[src:nanoputian/1-3-dioxolane] Organic compounds containing carbonyl groups sometimes need protection so that they do not undergo reactions during transformations of other functional groups that may be present.
[src:nanoputian/1-3-dioxolane] A variety of approaches to protection and deprotection of carbonyls including as dioxolanes are known.
[src:nanoputian/1-3-dioxolane] For example, consider the compound methyl cyclohexanone-4-carboxylate, where lithium aluminium hydride reduction will produce 4-hydroxymethylcyclohexanol.
[src:nanoputian/1-3-dioxolane] The ester functional group can be reduced without affecting the ketone by protecting the ketone as a ketal.
[src:nanoputian/1-3-dioxolane] The ketal is produced by acid catalysed reaction with ethylene glycol, the reduction reaction carried out, and the protecting group removed by hydrolysis to produce 4-hydroxymethylcyclohexanone.
[src:nanoputian/1-3-dioxolane] NaBArF4 can also be used for deprotection of acetal or ketal-protected carbonyl compounds.
[src:nanoputian/1-3-dioxolane] For example, deprotection of 2-phenyl-1,3-dioxolane to benzaldehyde can be achieved in water in five minutes at 30 °C.
[src:nanoputian/1-3-dioxolane] Neosporol is a natural product that includes a 1,3-dioxolane moiety, and is an isomer of sporol which has a 1,3-dioxane ring.
[src:nanoputian/1-3-dioxolane] The total synthesis of both compounds has been reported, and each includes a step in which a dioxolane system is formed using trifluoroperacetic acid (TFPAA), prepared by the hydrogen peroxide – urea method.
[src:nanoputian/1-3-dioxolane] This method involves no water, so it gives a completely anhydrous peracid, necessary in this case as the presence of water would lead to unwanted side reactions.
[src:nanoputian/1-3-dioxolane] In the case of neosporol, a Prilezhaev reaction with trifluoroperacetic acid is used to convert a suitable allyl alcohol precursor to an epoxide, which then undergoes a ring-expansion reaction with a proximate carbonyl functional group to form the dioxolane ring.
[src:nanoputian/1-3-dioxolane] A similar approach is used in the total synthesis of sporol, with the dioxolane ring later expanded to a dioxane system.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is the second simplest carboxylic acid (after formic acid).
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] It is an important chemical reagent and industrial chemical across various fields, used primarily in the production of cellulose acetate for photographic film, polyvinyl acetate for wood glue, and synthetic fibres and fabrics.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In households, diluted acetic acid is often used in descaling agents.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In the food industry, acetic acid is controlled by the food additive code E260 as an acidity regulator and as a condiment.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In biochemistry, the acetyl group, derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] When bound to coenzyme A, it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The global demand for acetic acid as of 2023 is about 17.88 million metric tonnes per year (t/a).
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Most of the world's acetic acid is produced via the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Its production and subsequent industrial use poses health hazards to workers, including incidental skin damage and chronic respiratory injuries from inhalation.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The trivial name "acetic acid" is the most commonly used and preferred IUPAC name.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The systematic name "ethanoic acid", a valid IUPAC name, is constructed according to the substitutive nomenclature.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The name "acetic acid" derives from the Latin word for vinegar, "*acetum*", which means "to sour" in relation to the bitter taste of fermented fruits.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] "Glacial acetic acid" is a name for water-free (anhydrous) acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Similar to the German name "Eisessig" ("ice vinegar"), the name comes from the solid ice-like crystals that form with agitation, slightly below room temperature at 16.6 °C (61.9 °F).
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can never be truly water-free in an atmosphere that contains water, so the presence of 0.1% water in glacial acetic acid lowers its melting point by 0.2 °C.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] A common symbol for acetic acid is AcOH (or HOAc), where Ac is the pseudoelement symbol representing the acetyl group CH3−C(=O)−; the conjugate base, acetate (CH3COO−), is thus represented as AcO−.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetate is the ion resulting from loss of H+ from acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The name "acetate" can also refer to a salt containing this anion, or an ester of acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] (The symbol Ac for the acetyl functional group is not to be confused with the symbol Ac for the element actinium; context prevents confusion among organic chemists).
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] To better reflect its structure, acetic acid is often written as CH3−C(O)OH, CH3−C(=O)−OH, CH3COOH, and CH3CO2H.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In the context of acid–base reactions, the abbreviation HAc is sometimes used, where Ac in this case is a symbol for acetate (rather than acetyl).
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The carboxymethyl functional group derived from removing one hydrogen from the methyl group of acetic acid has the chemical formula −CH2−C(=O)−OH.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid, the dilute solution of which is known as vinegar, is likely the first acid to be produced in large quantities in history.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Vinegar has been used for at least 10,000 years as it is the natural result of exposure of beer and wine to air because acetic acid-producing bacteria are present globally.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Hippocrates used vinegar as an antiseptic and as a remedy for numerous conditions including fever, constipation, ulcers, and pleurisy.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Ancient Romans boiled soured wine to produce a highly sweet syrup called *sapa*.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Sapa that was produced in lead pots was rich in lead acetate, a sweet substance also called *sugar of lead* or *sugar of Saturn*, which contributed to lead poisoning among the Roman aristocracy.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In the 16th-century German alchemist Andreas Libavius described the production of acetone from the dry distillation of lead acetate, ketonic decarboxylation.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The presence of water in vinegar has such a profound effect on acetic acid's properties that for centuries chemists believed that glacial acetic acid and the acid found in vinegar were two different substances.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] French chemist Pierre Adet proved them identical.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In 1845 German chemist Hermann Kolbe synthesized acetic acid from inorganic compounds for the first time.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] This reaction sequence consisted of chlorination of carbon disulfide to carbon tetrachloride, followed by pyrolysis to tetrachloroethylene and aqueous chlorination to trichloroacetic acid, and concluded with electrolytic reduction to acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] By 1910, most glacial acetic acid was obtained from pyroligneous liquor, a product of the destructive distillation of wood.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The acetic acid was isolated by treatment with milk of lime, and the resulting calcium acetate was then acidified with sulfuric acid to recover acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] At that time, Germany was producing 10,000 tons of glacial acetic acid, around 30% of which was used for the manufacture of indigo dye.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Because both methanol and carbon monoxide are commodity raw materials, methanol carbonylation long appeared to be an attractive method of acetic acid production.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Henri Dreyfus at British Celanese developed a methanol carbonylation pilot plant as early as 1925.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] However, a lack of practical materials that could contain the corrosive reaction mixture at the high pressures needed (200 atm or more) discouraged commercialization of these routes.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The first commercial methanol carbonylation process, which used a cobalt catalyst, was developed by German chemical company BASF in 1963.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In 1968, a rhodium-based catalyst (*cis*−[Rh(CO)2I2]−) was discovered that could operate efficiently at lower pressure with almost no by-products.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] US chemical company Monsanto Company built the first plant using this catalyst in 1970, and rhodium-catalyzed methanol carbonylation became the dominant method of acetic acid production (see Monsanto process).
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In the late 1990s, BP Chemicals commercialized the Cativa catalyst ([Ir(CO)2I2]−), which is promoted by iridium for greater efficiency.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Known as the Cativa process, the iridium-catalyzed production of glacial acetic acid is greener, and has largely supplanted the Monsanto process, often in the same production plants.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Interstellar acetic acid was first detected in the Sagittarius B2 North molecular cloud (also known as the Sgr B2 Large Molecule Heimat source).
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Because of this release of the proton (H+), acetic acid has acidic character.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In aqueous solution, it has a pKa value of 4.76.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Its conjugate base is acetate (CH3COO−).
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] A 1.0 M solution (about the concentration of domestic vinegar) has a pH of 2.4, indicating that merely 0.4% of the acetic acid molecules are ionized.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In solid acetic acid, the molecules form chains of individual molecules interconnected by hydrogen bonds.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In the vapour phase at 120 °C (248 °F), dimers can be detected.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Dimers also occur in the liquid phase in dilute solutions with non-hydrogen-bonding solvents, and to a certain extent in pure acetic acid, but are disrupted by hydrogen-bonding solvents.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The dissociation enthalpy of the dimer is estimated at 65.0–66.0 kJ/mol, and the dissociation entropy at 154–157 J mol−1 K−1.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Other carboxylic acids engage in similar intermolecular hydrogen bonding interactions.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Liquid acetic acid is a hydrophilic (polar) protic solvent, similar to ethanol and water.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] With a relative static permittivity (dielectric constant) of 6.2, it dissolves not only polar compounds such as inorganic salts and sugars, but also non-polar compounds such as oils as well as polar solutes.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] It is miscible with polar and non-polar solvents such as water, chloroform, and hexane.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] With higher alkanes (starting with octane), acetic acid is not miscible at all compositions, and solubility of acetic acid in alkanes declines with longer n-alkanes.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The solvent and miscibility properties of acetic acid make it a useful industrial chemical, for example, as a solvent in the production of dimethyl terephthalate.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] At physiological pHs, acetic acid is usually fully ionized to acetate in aqueous solution.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The acetyl group, formally derived from acetic acid, is fundamental to all forms of life.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Typically, it is bound to coenzyme A by acetyl-CoA synthetase enzymes, where it is central to the metabolism of carbohydrates and fats.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Unlike longer-chain carboxylic acids (the fatty acids), acetic acid does not occur in natural triglycerides.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Most of the acetate generated in cells for use in acetyl-CoA is synthesized directly from ethanol or pyruvate.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] However, the artificial triglyceride triacetin (glycerine triacetate) is a common food additive and is found in cosmetics and topical medicines; this additive is metabolized to glycerol and acetic acid in the body.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced and excreted by acetic acid bacteria, notably the genus *Acetobacter* and *Clostridium acetobutylicum*.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] These bacteria are found universally in foodstuffs, water, and soil, and acetic acid is produced naturally as fruits and other foods spoil.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is also a component of the vaginal lubrication of humans and other primates, where it appears to serve as a mild antibacterial agent.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is produced industrially both naturally via bacterial fermentation and synthetically.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] About 75% of acetic acid made for use in the chemical industry is made by the carbonylation of methanol, explained below.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The biological route accounts for only about 10% of world production, but it remains important for the production of vinegar because many food purity laws require vinegar used in foods to be of biological origin.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Other processes are methyl formate isomerization, conversion of syngas to acetic acid, and gas phase oxidation of ethylene and ethanol.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid can be purified via fractional freezing using an ice bath.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The water and other impurities will remain liquid while the acetic acid will precipitate out.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] As of 2003–2005, total worldwide production of virgin acetic acid was estimated at 5 Mt/a (million tonnes per year), approximately half of which was produced in the United States.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] European production was approximately 1 Mt/a and declining, while Japanese production was 0.7 Mt/a.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Another 1.5 Mt were recycled each year, bringing the total world market to 6.5 Mt/a.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Since then, the global production has increased from 10.7 Mt/a in 2010 to 17.88 Mt/a in 2023.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The two biggest producers of virgin acetic acid are Celanese and BP Chemicals.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Other major producers include Millennium Chemicals, Sterling Chemicals, Samsung, Eastman, and Svensk Etanolkemi.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Most acetic acid is produced by methanol carbonylation.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The process involves iodomethane as an intermediate, and occurs in three steps.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] A metal carbonyl catalyst is needed for the carbonylation (step 2).
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Two related processes exist for the carbonylation of methanol: the rhodium-catalyzed Monsanto process, and the iridium-catalyzed Cativa process.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The latter process is greener and more efficient and has largely supplanted the former process.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Catalytic amounts of water are used in both processes, but the Cativa process requires less, so the water-gas shift reaction is suppressed, and fewer by-products are formed.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] By altering the process conditions, acetic anhydride may also be produced in plants using rhodium catalysis.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Prior to the commercialization of the Monsanto process, most acetic acid was produced by oxidation of acetaldehyde.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] This remains the second-most-important manufacturing method, although it is usually not competitive with the carbonylation of methanol.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The acetaldehyde can be produced by hydration of acetylene.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] This was the dominant technology in the early 1900s.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Such oxidations require metal catalyst, such as the naphthenate salts of manganese, cobalt, and chromium.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The typical reaction is conducted at temperatures and pressures designed to be as hot as possible while still keeping the butane a liquid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Typical reaction conditions are 150 °C (302 °F) and 55 atm.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Side-products may also form, including butanone, ethyl acetate, formic acid, and propionic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] These side-products are also commercially valuable, and the reaction conditions may be altered to produce more of them where needed.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] However, the separation of acetic acid from these by-products adds to the cost of the process.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Similar conditions and catalysts are used for butane oxidation, the oxygen in air to produce acetic acid can oxidize acetaldehyde.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Using modern catalysts, this reaction can have an acetic acid yield greater than 95%.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The major side-products are ethyl acetate, formic acid, and formaldehyde, all of which have lower boiling points than acetic acid and are readily separated by distillation.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetaldehyde may be prepared from ethylene via the Wacker process, and then oxidized as above.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In more recent times, chemical company Showa Denko, which opened an ethylene oxidation plant in Ōita, Japan, in 1997, commercialized a cheaper single-stage conversion of ethylene to acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The process is catalyzed by a palladium metal catalyst supported on a heteropoly acid such as silicotungstic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] It is thought to be competitive with methanol carbonylation for smaller plants (100–250 kt/a), depending on the local price of ethylene.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] For most of human history, acetic acid bacteria of the genus *Acetobacter* have made acetic acid, in the form of vinegar.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Given sufficient oxygen, these bacteria can produce vinegar from a variety of alcoholic foodstuffs.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Commonly used feeds include apple cider, wine, and fermented grain, malt, rice, or potato mashes.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] A dilute alcohol solution inoculated with *Acetobacter* and kept in a warm, airy place will become vinegar over the course of a few months.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Industrial vinegar-making methods accelerate this process by improving the supply of oxygen to the bacteria.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The first batches of vinegar produced by fermentation probably followed errors in the winemaking process.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] If must is fermented at too high a temperature, acetobacter will overwhelm the yeast naturally occurring on the grapes.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] As the demand for vinegar for culinary, medical, and sanitary purposes increased, vintners quickly learned to use other organic materials to produce vinegar in the hot summer months before the grapes were ripe and ready for processing into wine.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] This method was slow, however, and not always successful, as the vintners did not understand the process.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] One of the first modern commercial processes was the "fast method" or "German method", first practised in Germany in 1823.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In this process, fermentation takes place in a tower packed with wood shavings or charcoal.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The alcohol-containing feed is trickled into the top of the tower, and fresh air supplied from the bottom by either natural or forced convection.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The improved air supply in this process cut the time to prepare vinegar from months to weeks.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Nowadays, most vinegar is made in submerged tank culture, first described in 1949 by Otto Hromatka and Heinrich Ebner.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In this method, alcohol is fermented to vinegar in a continuously stirred tank, and oxygen is supplied by bubbling air through the solution.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Using modern applications of this method, vinegar of 15% acetic acid can be prepared in only 24 hours in batch process, even 20% in 60-hour fed-batch process.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Species of anaerobic bacteria, including members of the genus *Clostridium* or *Acetobacterium*, can convert sugars to acetic acid directly without creating ethanol as an intermediate.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] This ability of *Clostridium* to metabolize sugars directly, or to produce acetic acid from less costly inputs, suggests that these bacteria could produce acetic acid more efficiently than ethanol-oxidizers like *Acetobacter*.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] However, *Clostridium* bacteria are less acid-tolerant than *Acetobacter*.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Even the most acid-tolerant *Clostridium* strains can produce vinegar in concentrations of only a few percent, compared to *Acetobacter* strains that can produce vinegar in concentrations up to 20%.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] At present, it remains more cost-effective to produce vinegar using *Acetobacter*, rather than using *Clostridium* and concentrating it.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] As a result, although acetogenic bacteria have been known since 1940, their industrial use is confined to a few niche applications.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is a chemical reagent for the production of chemical compounds.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The largest single use of acetic acid is in the production of vinyl acetate monomer, closely followed by acetic anhydride and ester production.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The volume of acetic acid used in vinegar is comparatively small.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The primary use of acetic acid is the production of vinyl acetate monomer (VAM).
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In 2008, this application was estimated to consume a third of the world's production of acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The reaction consists of ethylene and acetic acid with oxygen over a palladium catalyst, conducted in the gas phase.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Vinyl acetate can be polymerized to polyvinyl acetate or other polymers, which are components in paints and adhesives.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The major esters of acetic acid are commonly used as solvents for inks, paints and coatings.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The esters include ethyl acetate, *n*-butyl acetate, isobutyl acetate, and propyl acetate.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] For example, acetic acid and ethanol gives ethyl acetate and water.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Most acetate esters, however, are produced from acetaldehyde using the Tishchenko reaction.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In addition, ether acetates are used as solvents for nitrocellulose, acrylic lacquers, varnish removers, and wood stains.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] First, glycol monoethers are produced from ethylene oxide or propylene oxide with alcohol, which are then esterified with acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The three major products are ethylene glycol monoethyl ether acetate (EEA), ethylene glycol monobutyl ether acetate (EBA), and propylene glycol monomethyl ether acetate (PMA, more commonly known as PGMEA in semiconductor manufacturing processes, where it is used as a resist solvent).
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] This application consumes about 15% to 20% of worldwide acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Ether acetates, for example EEA, have been shown to be harmful to human reproduction.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The product of the condensation of two molecules of acetic acid is acetic anhydride.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The worldwide production of acetic anhydride is a major application, and uses approximately 25% to 30% of the global production of acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The main process involves dehydration of acetic acid to give ketene at 700–750 °C.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is an acetylation agent.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] As such, its major application is for cellulose acetate, a synthetic textile also used for photographic film, which is produced by reacting cellulose with acetic acid and acetic anhydride in the presence of sulfuric acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic anhydride is also a reagent for the production of heroin and other compounds.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] As a polar protic solvent, acetic acid is frequently used for recrystallization to purify organic compounds.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as a solvent in the production of terephthalic acid (TPA), the raw material for polyethylene terephthalate (PET).
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In 2006, about 20% of acetic acid was used for TPA production.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is often used as a solvent for reactions involving carbocations, such as Friedel-Crafts alkylation.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] For example, one stage in the commercial manufacture of synthetic camphor involves a Wagner-Meerwein rearrangement of camphene to isobornyl acetate; here acetic acid acts both as a solvent and as a nucleophile to trap the rearranged carbocation.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is used in analytical chemistry for the estimation of weakly alkaline substances such as organic amides.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Glacial acetic acid is a much weaker base than water, so the amide behaves as a strong base in this medium.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] It then can be titrated using a solution in glacial acetic acid of a very strong acid, such as perchloric acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid injection into a tumor has been used to treat cancer since the 1800s.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is used as part of cervical cancer screening in many areas in the developing world.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The acid is applied to the cervix and if an area of white appears after about a minute the test is positive.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid is an effective antiseptic when used as a 1% solution, with broad spectrum of activity against streptococci, staphylococci, pseudomonas, enterococci and others.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] It may be used to treat skin infections caused by pseudomonas strains resistant to typical antibiotics.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] While diluted acetic acid is used in iontophoresis, no high quality evidence supports this treatment for rotator cuff disease.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] As a treatment for otitis externa, it is on the World Health Organization's List of Essential Medicines.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Vinegar is typically no less than 4% acetic acid by mass.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Legal limits on acetic acid content vary by jurisdiction.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Vinegar is used directly as a condiment, and in the pickling of vegetables and other foods.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Table vinegar tends to be more diluted (4% to 8% acetic acid), while commercial food pickling employs solutions that are more concentrated.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The proportion of acetic acid used worldwide as vinegar is not as large as industrial uses, but it is by far the oldest and best-known application.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetic acid undergoes the typical chemical reactions of a carboxylic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Upon treatment with a standard base, it converts to metal acetate and water.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] With strong bases (e.g., organolithium reagents), it can be doubly deprotonated to give LiCH2COOLi.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The OH group is the main site of reaction, as illustrated by the conversion of acetic acid to acetyl chloride.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Other substitution derivatives include acetic anhydride; this anhydride is produced by loss of water from two molecules of acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Esters of acetic acid can likewise be formed via Fischer esterification, and amides can be formed.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Because aluminium forms a passivating acid-resistant film of aluminium oxide, aluminium tanks are used to transport acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Containers lined with glass, stainless steel or polyethylene are also used for this purpose.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] A colour reaction for salts of acetic acid is iron(III) chloride solution, which results in a deeply red colour that disappears after acidification.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] A more sensitive test uses lanthanum nitrate with iodine and ammonia to give a blue solution.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Acetates when heated with arsenic trioxide form cacodyl oxide, which can be detected by its malodorous vapours.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Organic or inorganic salts are produced from acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Halogenated acetic acids are produced from acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Amounts of acetic acid used in these other applications together account for another 5–10% of acetic acid use worldwide.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Prolonged inhalation exposure (eight hours) to acetic acid vapours at 10 ppm can produce some irritation of eyes, nose, and throat; at 100 ppm marked lung irritation and possible damage to lungs, eyes, and skin may result.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Vapour concentrations of 1,000 ppm cause marked irritation of eyes, nose and upper respiratory tract and cannot be tolerated.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] These predictions were based on animal experiments and industrial exposure.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] In 12 workers exposed for two or more years to an airborne average concentration of 51 ppm acetic acid (estimated), symptoms of conjunctive irritation, upper respiratory tract irritation, and hyperkeratotic dermatitis were produced.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Exposure to 50 ppm or more is intolerable to most persons and results in intensive lacrimation and irritation of the eyes, nose, and throat, with pharyngeal oedema and chronic bronchitis.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Unacclimatized humans experience extreme eye and nasal irritation at concentrations in excess of 25 ppm, and conjunctivitis from concentrations below 10 ppm has been reported.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid (≥ 25%) is corrosive to skin.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] These burns or blisters may not appear until hours after exposure.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] The hazardous properties of acetic acid are dependent on the concentration of the (typically aqueous) solution, with the most significant increases in hazard levels at thresholds of 25% and 90% acetic acid concentration by weight.
[src:nanoputian/acetic-acid] Concentrated acetic acid can be ignited only with difficulty at standard temperature and pressure, but becomes a flammable risk in temperatures greater than 39 °C (102 °F), and can form explosive mixtures with air at increased temperatures with explosive limits of 5.4–16% concentration.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] As an alkyne, acetylene is unsaturated because its two carbon atoms are bonded together in a triple bond.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The carbon–carbon triple bond places all four atoms in the same straight line, with CCH bond angles of 180°.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The triple bond in acetylene results in a high energy content that is released when acetylene is burned.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Acetylene was discovered in 1836 by Edmund Davy, who identified it as a "new carburet of hydrogen".
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] It was an accidental discovery while attempting to isolate potassium metal.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] By heating potassium carbonate with carbon at very high temperatures, he produced a residue of what is now known as potassium carbide, (K2C2), which reacted with water to release the new gas.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] It was rediscovered in 1860 by French chemist Marcellin Berthelot, who coined the name *acétylène*.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Berthelot's empirical formula for acetylene (C4H2), as well as the alternative name "*quadricarbure d'hydrogène*" (hydrogen quadricarbide), were incorrect because many chemists at that time used the wrong atomic mass for carbon (6 instead of 12).
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Berthelot was able to prepare this gas by passing vapours of organic compounds (methanol, ethanol, etc.) through a red hot tube and collecting the effluent.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] He also found that acetylene was formed by sparking electricity through mixed cyanogen and hydrogen gases.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Berthelot later obtained acetylene directly by passing hydrogen between the poles of a carbon arc.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] It is a recovered side product in production of ethylene by cracking of hydrocarbons.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Approximately 400,000 tonnes were produced by this method in 1983.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Its presence in ethylene is usually undesirable because of its explosive character and its ability to poison Ziegler–Natta catalysts.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] It is selectively hydrogenated into ethylene, usually using Pd–Ag catalysts.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] This last reaction is implemented in the process of anaerobic decomposition of methane by microwave plasma.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The first sample of acetylene produced was by Edmund Davy in 1836, via hydrolysis (decomposition using water) of potassium carbide.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] This reaction was discovered by Friedrich Wöhler in 1862, but a suitable commercial scale production method which allowed acetylene to be put into wider scale use was not found until 1892 by the Canadian inventor Thomas Willson while searching for a viable commercial production method for aluminum.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] As late as the early 21st century, China, Japan, and Eastern Europe produced acetylene primarily by this method.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The use of this technology has since declined worldwide with the notable exception of China, with its emphasis on coal-based chemical industry, as of 2013.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Otherwise oil has increasingly supplanted coal as the chief source of reduced carbon.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Calcium carbide production requires high temperatures, ~2000 °C, necessitating the use of an electric arc furnace.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] In the US, this process was an important part of the late-19th century revolution in chemistry enabled by the massive hydroelectric power project at Niagara Falls.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] In terms of valence bond theory, in each carbon atom the 2s orbital hybridizes with one 2p orbital thus forming an sp hybrid.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The other two 2p orbitals remain unhybridized.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The two ends of the two sp hybrid orbital overlap to form a strong σ valence bond between the carbons, while on each of the other two ends hydrogen atoms attach also by σ bonds.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The two unchanged 2p orbitals form a pair of weaker π bonds.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Since acetylene is a linear symmetrical molecule, it possesses the D∞h point group.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] At atmospheric pressure, acetylene cannot exist as a liquid and does not have a melting point.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The triple point on the phase diagram corresponds to the melting point (−80.8 °C) at the minimal pressure at which liquid acetylene can exist (1.27 atm).
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] At temperatures below the triple point, solid acetylene can change directly to the vapour (gas) by sublimation.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The sublimation point at atmospheric pressure is −84.0 °C.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] At room temperature and atmospheric pressure, the solubility of acetylene in acetone is 27.9 g per kg.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] For the same amount of dimethylformamide (DMF), the solubility is 51 g.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] At 20.26 bar, the solubility increases to 689.0 and 628.0 g for acetone and DMF, respectively.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] These solvents are used in pressurized gas cylinders.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Approximately 20% of acetylene is supplied by the industrial gases industry for oxyacetylene gas welding and cutting due to the high temperature of the flame.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Combustion of acetylene with oxygen produces a flame of over 3,600 K (3,330 °C; 6,020 °F), releasing 11.8 kJ/g.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Oxygen with acetylene is the hottest burning common gas mixture.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Oxy-acetylene welding was a popular welding process in previous decades.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The development and advantages of arc-based welding processes have made oxy-fuel welding nearly extinct for many applications.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Acetylene usage for welding has dropped significantly.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Bell Canada cable-repair technicians still use portable acetylene-fuelled torch kits as a soldering tool for sealing lead sleeve splices in manholes and in some aerial locations.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Oxyacetylene welding may also be used in areas where electricity is not readily accessible.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Oxyacetylene cutting is used in many metal fabrication shops.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] For use in welding and cutting, the working pressures must be controlled by a regulator, since above 15 psi (100 kPa), if subjected to a shockwave (caused, for example, by a flashback), acetylene decomposes explosively into hydrogen and carbon.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Acetylene is useful for many processes, but few are conducted on a commercial scale.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] One of the major chemical applications is ethynylation of formaldehyde.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The reaction gives butynediol, with propargyl alcohol as the by-product.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Copper acetylide is used as the catalyst.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] In addition to ethynylation, acetylene reacts with carbon monoxide to give acrylic acid, or acrylic esters.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] These derivatives form products such as acrylic fibers, glasses, paints, resins, and polymers.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Except in China, use of acetylene as a chemical feedstock has declined by 70% from 1965 to 2007 owing to cost and environmental considerations.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] In China, acetylene is a major precursor to vinyl chloride.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Prior to the widespread use of petrochemicals, coal-derived acetylene was a building block for several industrial chemicals.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Thus acetylene can be hydrated to give acetaldehyde, which in turn can be oxidized to acetic acid.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Processes leading to acrylates were also commercialized.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Almost all of these processes became obsolete with the availability of petroleum-derived ethylene and propylene.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] In 1881, the Russian chemist Mikhail Kucherov described the hydration of acetylene to acetaldehyde using catalysts such as mercury(II) bromide.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Before the advent of the Wacker process, this reaction was conducted on an industrial scale.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The polymerization of acetylene with Ziegler–Natta catalysts produces polyacetylene films.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Polyacetylene, a chain of CH centres with alternating single and double bonds, was one of the first discovered organic semiconductors.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Its reaction with iodine produces a highly electrically conducting material.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Although such materials are not useful, these discoveries led to the developments of organic semiconductors, as recognized by the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 2000 to Alan J.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Heeger, Alan G MacDiarmid, and Hideki Shirakawa.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] In the 1920s, pure acetylene was experimentally used as an inhalation anesthetic.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Acetylene is sometimes used for carburization (that is, hardening) of steel when the object is too large to fit into a furnace.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Acetylene is used to volatilize carbon in radiocarbon dating.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The carbonaceous material in an archeological sample is treated with lithium metal in a small specialized research furnace to form lithium carbide (also known as lithium acetylide).
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The carbide can then be reacted with water, as usual, to form acetylene gas to feed into a mass spectrometer to measure the isotopic ratio of carbon-14 to carbon-12.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Acetylene combustion produces a strong, bright light and the ubiquity of carbide lamps drove much acetylene commercialization in the early 20th century.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Common applications included coastal lighthouses, street lights, and automobile and mining headlamps.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] In most of these applications, direct combustion is a fire hazard, and so acetylene has been replaced, first by incandescent lighting and many years later by low-power/high-lumen LEDs.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Nevertheless, acetylene lamps remain in limited use in remote or otherwise inaccessible areas and in countries with a weak or unreliable central electric grid.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The energy richness of the C≡C triple bond and the rather high solubility of acetylene in water make it a suitable substrate for bacteria, provided an adequate source is available.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] A number of bacteria living on acetylene have been identified.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Acetylene is a moderately common chemical in the universe, often associated with the atmospheres of gas giants.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] One curious discovery of acetylene is on Enceladus, a moon of Saturn.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Natural acetylene is believed to form from catalytic decomposition of long-chain hydrocarbons at temperatures of 1,700 K (1,430 °C; 2,600 °F) and above.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Since such temperatures are highly unlikely on such a small distant body, this discovery is potentially suggestive of catalytic reactions within that moon, making it a promising site to search for prebiotic chemistry.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] In vinylation reactions, H−X compounds add across the triple bond.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Alcohols and phenols add to acetylene to give vinyl ethers.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Similarly, vinylpyrrolidone and vinylcarbazole are produced industrially by vinylation of 2-pyrrolidone and carbazole.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The hydration of acetylene is a vinylation reaction, but the resulting vinyl alcohol isomerizes to acetaldehyde.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The reaction is catalyzed by mercury salts.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] This reaction once was the dominant technology for acetaldehyde production, but it has been displaced by the Wacker process, which affords acetaldehyde by oxidation of ethylene, a cheaper feedstock.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] A similar situation applies to the conversion of acetylene to the valuable vinyl chloride by hydrochlorination versus the oxychlorination of ethylene.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Vinyl acetate is used instead of acetylene for some vinylations, which are more accurately described as transvinylations.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Higher esters of vinyl acetate have been used in the synthesis of vinyl formate.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Acetylene and its derivatives (2-butyne, diphenylacetylene, etc.) form complexes with transition metals.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Its bonding to the metal is somewhat similar to that of ethylene complexes.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Metal acetylides, species of the formula L*n*M−C2R, are also common.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Copper(I) acetylide and silver acetylide can be formed in aqueous solutions with ease due to a favorable solubility equilibrium.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Various organometallic and inorganic reagents are effective.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Acetylene can be semihydrogenated to ethylene, providing a feedstock for a variety of polyethylene plastics.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Acetylene is not especially toxic, but when generated from calcium carbide, or CaC2, it can contain toxic impurities such as traces of phosphine and arsine, which gives it a distinct garlic-like smell.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] It is also highly flammable, as are most light hydrocarbons, hence its use in welding.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Although it is stable at normal pressures and temperatures, if it is subjected to pressures as low as 15 psig it can explode.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] The safe limit for acetylene therefore is 101 kPagage, or 15 psig.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Additionally, if acetylene is initiated by intense heat or a shockwave, it can decompose explosively if the absolute pressure of the gas exceeds about 200 kilopascals (29 psi).
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] It is therefore supplied and stored dissolved in acetone or dimethylformamide (DMF), contained in a gas cylinder with a porous filling, which renders it safe to transport and use, given proper handling.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should be used in the upright position to avoid withdrawing acetone during use.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Information on safe storage of acetylene in upright cylinders is provided by the OSHA, Compressed Gas Association, United States Mine Safety and Health Administration (MSHA), EIGA, and other agencies.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Copper catalyses the decomposition of acetylene, and as a result acetylene should not be transported in copper pipes.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Cylinders should be stored in an area segregated from oxidizers to avoid exacerbated reaction in case of fire/leakage.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Acetylene cylinders should not be stored in confined spaces, enclosed vehicles, garages, and buildings, to avoid unintended leakage leading to explosive atmosphere.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] In the US, National Electric Code (NEC) requires consideration for hazardous areas including those where acetylene may be released during accidents or leaks.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Consideration may include electrical classification and use of listed Group A electrical components in US.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] Further information on determining the areas requiring special consideration is in NFPA 497.
[src:nanoputian/acetylene] In Europe, ATEX also requires consideration for hazardous areas where flammable gases may be released during accidents or leaks.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] In organic chemistry, an **alkyl group** is an alkane missing one hydrogen atom.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] The term *alkyl* is intentionally unspecific to include many possible substitutions.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] An acyclic alkyl has the general formula of −C*n*H2*n*+1.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] A **cycloalkyl group** is derived from a cycloalkane by removal of a hydrogen atom from a ring and has the general formula −C*n*H2*n*−1.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] Typically an alkyl is a part of a larger molecule.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] In structural formulae, the symbol R is used to designate a generic (unspecified) alkyl group.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] The smallest alkyl group is methyl, with the formula −CH3.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] Alkylation is the addition of alkyl groups to molecules, often by alkylating agents such as alkyl halides.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] Alkylating antineoplastic agents are a class of compounds that are used to treat cancer.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] In such case, the term alkyl is used loosely.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] For example, nitrogen mustards are well-known alkylating agents, but they are not simple hydrocarbons.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] In chemistry, alkyl is a group, a substituent, that is attached to other molecular fragments.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] For example, alkyl lithium reagents have the empirical formula Li(alkyl), where alkyl = methyl, ethyl, etc.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] A *dialkyl* ether is an ether with two alkyl groups, e.g., diethyl ether O(CH2CH3)2.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] In medicinal chemistry, the incorporation of alkyl chains into some chemical compounds increases their lipophilicity.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] This strategy has been used to increase the antimicrobial activity of flavanones and chalcones.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] Usually, alkyl groups are attached to other atoms or groups of atoms.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] Free alkyls occur as neutral radicals, as anions, or as cations.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] The neutral alkyl free radicals have no special name.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] Such species are usually encountered only as transient intermediates.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] However, persistent alkyl radicals with half-lives "from seconds to years" have been prepared.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] Typically alkyl cations are generated using superacids and alkyl anions are observed in the presence of strong bases.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] Alkyl radicals can be generated by a photochemical reaction or by homolytic cleavage.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] Alkyls are commonly observed in mass spectrometry of organic compounds.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] Simple alkyls (especially methyl) are observed in the interstellar space as well.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] The simplest series have the general formula −C*n*H2*n*+1.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] Alkyl groups that contain one ring have the formula −C*n*H2*n*−1, e.g. cyclopropyl and cyclohexyl.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] The formula of alkyl radicals are the same as alkyl groups, except the free valence "−" is replaced by the dot "•" and adding "radical" to the name of the alkyl group (e.g. methyl radical •CH3).
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] The structure of 3-methylpentane is viewed as consisting of two parts.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] First, five atoms comprise the longest straight chain of carbon centers.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] The parent five-carbon compound is named pentane (highlighted blue).
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] The methyl "substituent" or "group" is highlighted red.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] According to the usual rules of nomenclature, alkyl groups are included in the name of the molecule before the root, as in methylpentane.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] This name is, however, ambiguous, as the methyl branch could be on various carbon atoms.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] Thus, the name is 3-methylpentane to avoid ambiguity: The 3- is because the methyl is attached to the third of the five carbon atoms.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] This compound is known as 2,3,3-trimethylpentane.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] Here three identical alkyl groups attached to carbon atoms 2, 3, and 3.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] The numbers are included in the name to avoid ambiguity about the position of the groups, and "tri" indicates that there are three identical methyl groups.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] If one of the methyl groups attached to the third carbon atom were instead an ethyl group, then the name would be 3-ethyl-2,3-dimethylpentane.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] When there are different alkyl groups, they are listed in alphabetical order.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] In addition, each position on an alkyl chain can be described according to how many other carbon atoms are attached to it.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] The terms primary, secondary, tertiary, and quaternary refer to a carbon attached to one, two, three, or four other carbons respectively.
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] The first named alkyl radical was ethyl, named so by Liebig in 1833 from the German word "Äther" (which in turn had been derived from the Greek word "aither" meaning "air", for the substance now known as diethyl ether) and the Greek word ύλη (hyle), meaning "matter".
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] This was followed by methyl (Dumas and Peligot in 1834, meaning "spirit of wood") and amyl (Auguste Cahours in 1840).
[src:nanoputian/alkyl-group] The word alkyl was introduced by Johannes Wislicenus in or before 1882, based on the German word "Alkoholradikale" and then-common suffix -yl.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] The concentration of such solutions is measured in units of the Baumé scale (density), with 26 degrees Baumé (about 30% of ammonia by weight at 15.5 °C or 59.9 °F) being the typical high-concentration commercial product.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Like other gases, ammonia exhibits decreasing solubility in solvent liquids as the temperature of the solvent increases.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Ammonia solutions decrease in density as the concentration of dissolved ammonia increases.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] At 15.6 °C (60.1 °F), the density of a saturated solution is 0.88 g/ml; it contains 35.6% ammonia by mass, 308 grams of ammonia per litre of solution, and has a molarity of approximately 18 mol/L.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] At higher temperatures, the molarity of the saturated solution decreases and the density increases.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Upon warming of saturated solutions, ammonia gas is released.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] In contrast to anhydrous ammonia, aqueous ammonia finds few non-niche uses outside of cleaning agents.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Ammonia solutions are used as cleaning products for many surfaces and applications.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Ammonia in water is sold as a cleaning agent by itself, usually labeled as simply "ammonia", as well as in cleaning products combined with other ingredients.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] It may be sold plain, lemon-scented (and typically colored yellow), or pine-scented (green).
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Commonly available ammonia with soap added is known as "cloudy ammonia".
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Household ammonia ranges in concentration by weight from 5% to 10% ammonia.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Because aqueous ammonia is a gas dissolved in water, as the water evaporates from a surface, the gas evaporates also, leaving the surface streak-free.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Its most common uses are to clean glass, porcelain, and stainless steel.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] It is good at removing grease and is found in products for cleaning ovens and for soaking items to loosen baked-on grime.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Experts also warn not to use ammonia-based cleaners on car touchscreens, due to the risk of damage to the screen's anti-glare and anti-fingerprint coatings.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] More concentrated solutions (higher than 10%) are used for in professional and industrial cleaning products.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] US manufacturers of cleaning products are required to provide the product's material safety data sheet that lists the concentration used.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] These solutions are irritating to the eyes and mucous membranes (respiratory and digestive tracts), and to a lesser extent the skin.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Experts advise that caution be used to ensure the chemical is not mixed into any liquid containing bleach, due to the danger of forming toxic chloramine gas.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Mixing with chlorine-containing products or strong oxidants, such as household bleach, can generate toxic chloramine fumes.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] In industry, aqueous ammonia can be used as a precursor to some alkyl amines, although anhydrous ammonia is usually preferred.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Hexamethylenetetramine forms readily from aqueous ammonia and formaldehyde.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Ethylenediamine forms from 1,2-dichloroethane and aqueous ammonia.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Both the absorption refrigerator and the Einstein refrigerator are well known examples of this application of the ammonia solution.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Ammonia is used to produce chloramine, which may be utilised as a disinfectant.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] In drinking water, chloramine is preferred over direct chlorination for its ability to remain active in stagnant water pipes longer, thereby reducing the risk of waterborne infections.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Ammonia is used by aquarists for the purposes of setting up a new fish tank using an ammonia process called fishless cycling.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] This application requires that the ammonia contain no additives.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Baking ammonia (ammonium carbonate and ammonium bicarbonate) was one of the original chemical leavening agents.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] It is useful as a leavening agent, because ammonium carbonate is heat activated.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] This characteristic allows bakers to avoid both yeast's long proofing time and the quick CO2 dissipation of baking soda in making breads and cookies rise.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] It is still used to make ammonia cookies and other crisp baked goods, but its popularity has waned because of ammonia's off-putting smell and concerns over its use as a food ingredient compared to modern-day baking powder formulations.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] It has been assigned E number E527 for use as a food additive in the European Union.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Aqueous ammonia is used as an acidity regulator to bring down the acid levels in food.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] It is classified in the United States by the Food and Drug Administration as generally recognized as safe (GRAS) when using the food grade version.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Its pH control abilities make it an effective antimicrobial agent.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] In furniture-making, ammonia fuming was traditionally used to darken or stain wood containing tannic acid.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] After being sealed inside a container with the wood, fumes from the ammonia solution react with the tannic acid and iron salts naturally found in wood, creating a rich, dark stained look to the wood.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] This technique was commonly used during the Arts and Crafts movement in furniture – a furniture style which was primarily constructed of oak and stained using these methods.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Aqueous ammonia is used in traditional qualitative inorganic analysis as a complexant and base.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Like many amines, it gives a deep blue coloration with copper(II) solutions.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] Ammonia solution can dissolve silver oxide residues, such as those formed from Tollens' reagent.
[src:nanoputian/ammonium-hydroxide] It is often found in solutions used to clean gold, silver, and platinum jewelry, but may have adverse effects on porous gem stones like opals and pearls.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene is a natural constituent of petroleum and is one of the elementary petrochemicals.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Because of the cyclic continuous pi bonds between the carbon atoms and satisfying the rules of aromaticity and Hückel's rule, benzene is classed as an aromatic hydrocarbon.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene is a colorless and highly flammable liquid with a sweet smell, and is partially responsible for the aroma of gasoline.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] It is used primarily as a precursor to the manufacture of chemicals with more complex structures, such as ethylbenzene and cumene, of which billions of kilograms are produced annually.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Although benzene is a major industrial chemical, it finds limited use in consumer items because of its toxicity.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Its particular effects on human health, such as the long-term results of accidental exposure, have been reported on by news organizations such as *The New York Times*.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] For instance, a 2022 article stated that benzene contamination in the Boston metropolitan area created hazards in multiple places and may eventually cause some cases of leukemia.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The word "*benzene*" derives from "*gum benzoin*" (benzoin resin), an aromatic resin known since ancient times in Southeast Asia, and later to European pharmacists and perfumers in the 16th century via trade routes.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] An acidic material was derived from benzoin by sublimation, and named "flowers of benzoin", or benzoic acid.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The hydrocarbon derived from benzoic acid thus acquired the names *benzin*, *benzol*, and *benzene*.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Michael Faraday first isolated and identified benzene in 1825 from the oily residue derived from the production of illuminating gas, giving it the name *bicarburet of hydrogen*.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In 1833, Eilhard Mitscherlich produced it by distilling benzoic acid (from gum benzoin) and lime.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In 1836, the French chemist Auguste Laurent named the substance "phène"; this word has become the root of the English word "phenol", which is hydroxylated benzene, and "phenyl", the radical formed by abstraction of a hydrogen atom from benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In 1845, Charles Blachford Mansfield, working under August Wilhelm von Hofmann, isolated benzene from coal tar.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Four years later, Mansfield began the first industrial-scale production of benzene, based on the coal-tar method.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Gradually, the sense developed among chemists that a number of substances were chemically related to benzene, comprising a diverse chemical family.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In 1855, Hofmann was the first to apply the word "aromatic" to designate this family relationship, after a characteristic property of many of its members.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In 1997, benzene was detected in deep space.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The empirical formula for benzene was long known, but its highly polyunsaturated structure, with just one hydrogen atom for each carbon atom, was challenging to determine.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] But many chemists had begun to work on aromatic substances, especially in Germany, and relevant data was coming fast.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In 1865, the German chemist Friedrich August Kekulé published a paper in French (for he was then teaching in Francophone Belgium) suggesting that the structure contained a ring of six carbon atoms with alternating single and double bonds.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The next year he published a much longer paper in German on the same subject.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Kekulé's symmetrical ring could explain these curious facts, as well as benzene's 1:1 carbon-hydrogen ratio.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The new understanding of benzene, and hence of all aromatic compounds, proved to be so important for both pure and applied chemistry that in 1890 the German Chemical Society organized an elaborate appreciation in Kekulé's honor, celebrating the twenty-fifth anniversary of his first benzene paper.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Here Kekulé spoke of the creation of the theory.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] He said that he had discovered the ring shape of the benzene molecule after having a reverie or day-dream of a snake biting its own tail (a symbol in ancient cultures known as the ouroboros).
[src:nanoputian/benzene] This vision, he said, came to him after years of studying the nature of carbon-carbon bonds.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] This was seven years after he had solved the problem of how carbon atoms could bond to up to four other atoms at the same time.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Some historians have suggested that the parody was a lampoon of the snake anecdote, possibly already well known through oral transmission even if it had not yet appeared in print.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Kekulé's 1890 speech in which this anecdote appeared has been translated into English.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] If the anecdote is the memory of a real event, circumstances mentioned in the story suggest that it must have happened early in 1862.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In 1929, the cyclic nature of benzene was finally confirmed by the crystallographer Kathleen Lonsdale using X-ray diffraction methods.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Using large crystals of hexamethylbenzene, a benzene derivative with the same core of six carbon atoms, Lonsdale obtained diffraction patterns.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Through calculating more than thirty parameters, Lonsdale demonstrated that the benzene ring could not be anything but a flat hexagon, and provided accurate distances for all carbon-carbon bonds in the molecule.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The German chemist Wilhelm Körner suggested the prefixes ortho-, meta-, para- to distinguish di-substituted benzene derivatives in 1867; however, he did not use the prefixes to distinguish the relative positions of the substituents on a benzene ring.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] It was the German chemist Carl Gräbe who, in 1869, first used the prefixes ortho-, meta-, para- to denote specific relative locations of the substituents on a di-substituted aromatic ring (viz, naphthalene).
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In 1870, the German chemist Viktor Meyer first applied Gräbe's nomenclature to benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In 1903, Ludwig Roselius popularized the use of benzene to decaffeinate coffee.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] This discovery led to the production of Sanka.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene was historically used as a significant component in many consumer products such as liquid wrench, several paint strippers, rubber cements, spot removers, and other products.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Manufacture of some of these benzene-containing formulations ceased in about 1950, although Liquid Wrench continued to contain significant amounts of benzene until the late 1970s.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Trace amounts of benzene are found in petroleum and coal.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] It is a byproduct of the incomplete combustion of many materials.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] For commercial use, until World War II, much of benzene was obtained as a by-product of coke production (or "coke-oven light oil") for the steel industry.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] However, in the 1950s, increased demand for benzene, especially from the growing polymers industry, necessitated the production of benzene from petroleum.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Today, most benzene comes from the petrochemical industry, with only a small fraction being produced from coal.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] X-ray diffraction reveals that benzene is a planar molecule with six-fold rotational symmetry, which is in the symmetry group, $D_{6h}$ .
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The carbon-carbon bond lengths of benzene are 140 picometers (pm) long, which are greater than a C=C double bond (135 pm) but shorter than a C-C single bond (147 pm).
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In terms of bonding, the molecular orbital (MO) description involves three bonding pi-MOs.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] A valence bond description involves a superposition of resonance structures.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Its considerable stability and distinctive chemical properties a manifested in the phenomenon of aromaticity.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] To reflect the delocalized nature of the bonding, benzene is often depicted with a circle inside a hexagonal arrangement of carbon atoms.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Many important chemical compounds are derived from benzene by replacing one or more of its hydrogen atoms with another functional group.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Examples of simple benzene derivatives are phenol, toluene, and aniline, abbreviated PhOH, PhMe, and PhNH2, respectively.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Linking benzene rings gives biphenyl, C6H5–C6H5.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Further loss of hydrogen gives "fused" aromatic hydrocarbons, such as naphthalene, anthracene, phenanthrene, and pyrene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The limit of the fusion process is the hydrogen-free allotrope of carbon, graphite.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In heterocycles, carbon atoms in the benzene ring are replaced with other elements.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The most important variations contain nitrogen.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Replacing one CH with N gives the compound pyridine, C5H5N.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Although benzene and pyridine are *structurally* related, benzene cannot be converted into pyridine.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Replacement of a second CH bond with N gives, depending on the location of the second N, pyridazine, pyrimidine, or pyrazine.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Four chemical processes contribute to industrial benzene production: catalytic reforming, toluene hydrodealkylation, toluene disproportionation, and steam cracking etc.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] According to the ATSDR Toxicological Profile for benzene, between 1978 and 1981, catalytic reformates accounted for approximately 44–50% of the total US benzene production.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In catalytic reforming, a mixture of hydrocarbons with boiling points between 60 and 200 °C is blended with hydrogen gas and then exposed to a bifunctional platinum chloride or rhenium chloride catalyst at 500–525 °C and pressures ranging from 8–50 atm.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Under these conditions, aliphatic hydrocarbons form rings and lose hydrogen to become aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The aromatic products of the reaction are then separated from the reaction mixture (or reformate) by extraction with any one of a number of solvents, including diethylene glycol or sulfolane, and benzene is then separated from the other aromatics by distillation.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The extraction step of aromatics from the reformate is designed to produce aromatics with lowest non-aromatic components.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Recovery of the aromatics, commonly referred to as BTX (benzene, toluene and xylene isomers), involves such extraction and distillation steps.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In similar fashion to this catalytic reforming, UOP and BP commercialized a method from LPG (mainly propane and butane) to aromatics.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Toluene hydrodealkylation converts toluene to benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In this hydrogen-intensive process, toluene is mixed with hydrogen, then passed over a chromium, molybdenum, or platinum oxide catalyst at 500–650 °C and 20–60 atm pressure.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Sometimes, higher temperatures are used instead of a catalyst (at the similar reaction condition).
[src:nanoputian/benzene] If the raw material stream contains much non-aromatic components (paraffins or naphthenes), those are likely decomposed to lower hydrocarbons such as methane, which increases the consumption of hydrogen.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Sometimes, xylenes and heavier aromatics are used in place of toluene, with similar efficiency.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] This is often called "on-purpose" methodology to produce benzene, compared to conventional BTX (benzene-toluene-xylene) extraction processes.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Toluene disproportionation (**TDP**) is the conversion of toluene to benzene and xylene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Given that demand for *para*-xylene (*p*-xylene) substantially exceeds demand for other xylene isomers, a refinement of the TDP process called **Selective TDP** (STDP) may be used.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In this process, the xylene stream exiting the TDP unit is approximately 90% *p*-xylene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In some systems, even the benzene-to-xylenes ratio is modified to favor xylenes.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Steam cracking is the process for producing ethylene and other alkenes from aliphatic hydrocarbons.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Depending on the feedstock used to produce the olefins, steam cracking can produce a benzene-rich liquid by-product called *pyrolysis gasoline*.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Pyrolysis gasoline can be blended with other hydrocarbons as a gasoline additive, or routed through an extraction process to recover BTX aromatics (benzene, toluene and xylenes).
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Although of no commercial significance, many other routes to benzene exist.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Phenol and halobenzenes can be reduced with metals.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzoic acid and its salts undergo decarboxylation to benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The reaction of the diazonium compound derived from aniline with hypophosphorus acid gives benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Alkyne trimerisation of acetylene gives benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Complete decarboxylation of mellitic acid gives benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene is used mainly as an intermediate to make other chemicals, above all ethylbenzene (and other alkylbenzenes), cumene, cyclohexane, and nitrobenzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In 1988, it was reported that two-thirds of all chemicals on the American Chemical Society's lists contained at least one benzene ring.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] More than half of the entire benzene production is processed into ethylbenzene, a precursor to styrene, which is used to make polymers and plastics like polystyrene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Some 20% of the benzene production is used to manufacture cumene, which is needed to produce phenol and acetone for resins and adhesives.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Cyclohexane consumes around 10% of the world's benzene production; it is primarily used in the manufacture of nylon fibers, which are processed into textiles and engineering plastics.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Smaller amounts of benzene are used to make some types of rubbers, lubricants, dyes, detergents, drugs, explosives, and pesticides.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In 2013, the biggest consumer country of benzene was China, followed by the USA.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene production is currently expanding in the Middle East and in Africa, whereas production capacities in Western Europe and North America are stagnating.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Toluene is now often used as a substitute for benzene, for instance as a fuel additive.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The solvent-properties of the two are similar, but toluene is less toxic and has a wider liquid range.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] As a gasoline (petrol) additive, benzene increases the octane rating and reduces knocking.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] As a consequence, gasoline often contained several percent benzene before the 1950s, when tetraethyl lead replaced it as the most widely used antiknock additive.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] With the global phaseout of leaded gasoline in the 1970s–1990s, benzene reappeared as a gasoline additive, although strictly limited in most nations.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] For example, in the United States, concern over its negative health effects and the possibility of benzene entering the groundwater has led to stringent regulation of gasoline's benzene content, with limits typically around 1%.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] European petrol specifications now contain the same 1% limit on benzene content.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The United States Environmental Protection Agency introduced new regulations in 2011 that lowered the benzene content in gasoline to 0.62%.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In some European languages, the word for petroleum or gasoline is an exact cognate of "benzene".
[src:nanoputian/benzene] For instance all Germanic languages and Scandinavian languages refer to gasoline as 'bensin' or 'benzin'.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In Turkish and many Turkic languages the word of 'benzin' is used to refer the gasoline.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In Catalan and Italian the word 'benzina' can be used for gasoline.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In both Polish and Greek the word 'benzyna' is also used to mean gasoline or petrol.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The most common reactions of benzene involve substitution of a proton by other groups.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Electrophilic aromatic substitution is a general method of derivatizing benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene is sufficiently nucleophilic that it undergoes substitution by acylium ions and alkyl carbocations to give substituted derivatives.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The most widely practiced example of this reaction is the ethylation of benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Approximately 24,700,000 tons of ethylbenzene were produced in 1999.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Highly instructive but of far less industrial significance is the Friedel-Crafts alkylation of benzene (and many other aromatic rings) using an alkyl halide in the presence of a strong Lewis acid catalyst.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Similarly, the Friedel-Crafts acylation is a related example of electrophilic aromatic substitution.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The reaction involves the acylation of benzene (or many other aromatic rings) with an acyl chloride using a strong Lewis acid catalyst such as aluminium chloride or Iron(III) chloride.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Using electrophilic aromatic substitution, many functional groups are introduced onto the benzene framework.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Sulfonation of benzene involves the use of oleum, a mixture of sulfuric acid with sulfur trioxide.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Sulfonated benzene derivatives are useful detergents.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In nitration, benzene reacts with nitronium ions (NO2+), which is a strong electrophile produced by combining sulfuric and nitric acids.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Nitrobenzene is the precursor to aniline.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Chlorination is achieved with chlorine to produce chlorobenzene in the presence of a Lewis acid catalyst such as aluminium chloride.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Hydrogenation is achieved by introducing hydrogen to the unsaturated compounds under high pressure in the presence of heterogeneous catalysts, such as finely divided nickel.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] This reaction converts benzene into cyclohexane.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene derivatives are also converted into their respective saturated equivalents.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Whereas alkenes can be hydrogenated near room temperatures, benzene and its derivatives are more reluctant substrates, requiring temperatures exceeding 100 °C for hydrogenation to occur.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] This reaction is practiced on an industrial scale.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Typically, benzene is fully saturated into cyclohexane during hydrogenation.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] However, with the right conditions, benzene can be partially-hydrogenated to give cyclohexene or cyclohexadienes.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] A similar reaction is the Birch reduction, which is a non-catalytic process that converts benzene into cyclohexadiene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene is an excellent ligand in the organometallic chemistry of low-valent metals.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Complexes containing benzene include the sandwich complex Cr(C6H6)2 as well as the half-sandwich complex [RuCl2(C6H6)]2.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene is classified as a carcinogen, which increases the risk of cancer and other illnesses, and is also a notorious cause of bone marrow failure.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Substantial quantities of epidemiologic, clinical, and laboratory data link benzene to aplastic anemia, acute leukemia, bone marrow abnormalities and cardiovascular disease.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The specific hematologic malignancies that benzene is associated with include: acute myeloid leukemia (AML), aplastic anemia, myelodysplastic syndrome (MDS), acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL), and chronic myeloid leukemia (CML).
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Carcinogenic activity of benzene was discovered by Swedish pharmacologist C.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Santesson in 1897 on female workers of a tire-making factory.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The American Petroleum Institute (API) stated in 1948 that "it is generally considered that the only absolutely safe concentration for benzene is zero".
[src:nanoputian/benzene] There is no safe exposure level; even tiny amounts can cause harm.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The US Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) classifies benzene as a human carcinogen.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Long-term exposure to excessive levels of benzene in the air causes leukemia, a potentially fatal cancer of the blood-forming organs.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In particular, acute myeloid leukemia or acute nonlymphocytic leukemia (AML & ANLL) is caused by benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] IARC rated benzene as "known to be carcinogenic to humans" (Group 1).
[src:nanoputian/benzene] As benzene is ubiquitous in gasoline and hydrocarbon fuels that are in use everywhere, human exposure to benzene is a global health problem.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene targets the liver, kidney, lung, heart and brain and can cause DNA strand breaks and chromosomal damage, therefore it is mutagenic.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene causes cancer in animals including humans.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene has been shown to cause cancer in both sexes of multiple species of laboratory animals exposed via various routes.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The major sources of benzene exposure are tobacco smoke, automobile service stations, exhaust from motor vehicles, and industrial emissions; however, ingestion and dermal absorption of benzene can also occur through contact with contaminated water.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene is hepatically metabolized and excreted in the urine.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Measurement of air and water levels of benzene is accomplished through collection via activated charcoal tubes, which are then analyzed with a gas chromatograph.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The measurement of benzene in humans can be accomplished via urine, blood, and breath tests; however, all of these have their limitations because benzene is rapidly metabolized in the human body.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Exposure to benzene may lead progressively to aplastic anemia, leukaemia, and multiple myeloma.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) regulates levels of benzene in the workplace.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The maximum allowable amount of benzene in workroom air during an 8-hour workday, 40-hour workweek is 1 ppm.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] As benzene can cause cancer, National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) recommends that all workers wear special breathing equipment when they are likely to be exposed to benzene at levels exceeding the recommended (8-hour) exposure limit of 0.1 ppm.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The United States Environmental Protection Agency has set a maximum contaminant level for benzene in drinking water at 0.005 mg/L (5 ppb), as promulgated via the US National Primary Drinking Water Regulations.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] This regulation is based on preventing benzene leukemogenesis.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The maximum contaminant level goal (MCLG), a nonenforceable health goal that would allow an adequate margin of safety for the prevention of adverse effects, is zero benzene concentration in drinking water.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The EPA requires that spills or accidental releases into the environment of 10 pounds (4.5 kg) or more of benzene be reported.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The US Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has set a permissible exposure limit of 1 part of benzene per million parts of air (1 ppm) in the workplace during an 8-hour workday, 40-hour workweek.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The short term exposure limit for airborne benzene is 5 ppm for 15 minutes.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] These legal limits were based on studies demonstrating compelling evidence of health risk to workers exposed to benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The risk from exposure to 1 ppm for a working lifetime has been estimated as 5 excess leukemia deaths per 1,000 employees exposed.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] (This estimate assumes no threshold for benzene's carcinogenic effects.) OSHA has also established an action level of 0.5 ppm to encourage even lower exposures in the workplace.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The US National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) revised the Immediately Dangerous to Life and Health (IDLH) concentration for benzene to 500 ppm.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In September 1995, NIOSH issued a new policy for developing recommended exposure limits (RELs) for substances, including carcinogens.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] As benzene can cause cancer, NIOSH recommends that all workers wear special breathing equipment when they are likely to be exposed to benzene at levels exceeding the REL (10-hour) of 0.1 ppm.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The NIOSH short-term exposure limit (STEL – 15 min) is 1 ppm.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] American Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists (ACGIH) adopted Threshold Limit Values (TLVs) for benzene at 0.02 ppm TWA in 2024.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Germany’s regulation comes through something called Technische Regeln für Gefahrstoffe which means Germany’s Technical Rule For Hazardous Substances.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The workspace exposure limit in Germany is TRGS 900.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Whereas the TRGS 910 sets the level of risk for the chemicals that can cause cancer and explains the amount that should be reduced.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] When it comes to the EU exposure limit it’s about 0.66 mg^3.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] When looking at TRGS 910 according to the numbers from national assessment criteria the target concentration is AC: 0.2 mg/m3 and the temporary upper concentration level is TC: 1.9 mg/m3.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Scientific research shows that there is correlation between leukemia and benzene exposure; average exposure to benzene below 5μg/m^3 lowered the leukemia burden from benzene by nearly a third.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] This information from the VegAS project shows how trying to control the level of benzene has a lot of importance since it has caused problems in the country.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] This project was funded by The Federal Ministry of Environment, Nature Conservation.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In terms of the benzene market, Germany is a top 3 producer in the European Union.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] It is the BASF that has responsibility when it comes to looking over chemicals such as benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Also, Germany is in the top 6 when it comes to the exports in the world for benzene, same when it comes to imports.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] They are the 7th largest importers in the world as well.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] When looking at the EU, they are one of the largest traders when it comes to benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Several tests can determine exposure to benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene itself can be measured in breath, blood, or urine, however such testing is usually limited to the first 24 hours post-exposure due to the relatively rapid removal of the chemical by exhalation or biotransformation.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The majority of people in developed countries have measureable baseline levels of benzene and other aromatic petroleum hydrocarbons in their blood.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In the body, benzene is enzymatically converted to a series of oxidation products including muconic acid, phenylmercapturic acid, phenol, catechol, hydroquinone and 1,2,4-trihydroxybenzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Most of these metabolites have some value as biomarkers of human exposure, since they accumulate in the urine in proportion to the extent and duration of exposure, and they may still be present for some days after exposure has ceased.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The current ACGIH biological exposure limits for occupational exposure are 500 μg/g creatinine for muconic acid and 25 μg/g creatinine for phenylmercapturic acid in an end-of-shift urine specimen.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Even if it is not a common substrate for metabolism, benzene can be oxidized by both bacteria and eukaryotes.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In bacteria, dioxygenase enzyme can add an oxygen to the ring, and the unstable product is immediately reduced (by NADH) to a cyclic diol with two double bonds, breaking the aromaticity.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Next, the diol is newly reduced by NADH to catechol.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The catechol is then metabolized to acetyl CoA and succinyl CoA, used by organisms mainly in the citric acid cycle for energy production.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Human metabolism of benzene is complex and begins in the liver.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] These include cytochrome P450 2E1 (CYP2E1), quinine oxidoreductase (NQ01 or DT-diaphorase or NAD(P)H dehydrogenase (quinone 1)), GSH, and myeloperoxidase (MPO).
[src:nanoputian/benzene] CYP2E1 is involved at multiple steps: converting benzene to oxepin (benzene oxide), phenol to hydroquinone, and hydroquinone to both benzenetriol and catechol.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Hydroquinone, benzenetriol and catechol are converted to polyphenols.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In the bone marrow, MPO converts these polyphenols to benzoquinones.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] NQ01 and GSH shift metabolism away from toxicity.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] NQ01 metabolizes benzoquinone toward polyphenols (counteracting the effect of MPO).
[src:nanoputian/benzene] GSH is involved with the formation of phenylmercapturic acid.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Genetic polymorphisms in these enzymes may induce loss of function or gain of function.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] For example, mutations in CYP2E1 increase activity and result in increased generation of toxic metabolites.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] NQ01 mutations result in loss of function and may result in decreased detoxification.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Myeloperoxidase mutations result in loss of function and may result in decreased generation of toxic metabolites.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] GSH mutations or deletions result in loss of function and result in decreased detoxification.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] These genes may be targets for genetic screening for susceptibility to benzene toxicity.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The paradigm of toxicological assessment of benzene is shifting towards the domain of molecular toxicology as it allows understanding of fundamental biological mechanisms in a better way.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Glutathione seems to play an important role by protecting against benzene-induced DNA breaks and it is being identified as a new biomarker for exposure and effect.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene causes chromosomal aberrations in the peripheral blood leukocytes and bone marrow explaining the higher incidence of leukemia and multiple myeloma caused by chronic exposure.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] These aberrations can be monitored using fluorescent in situ hybridization (FISH) with DNA probes to assess the effects of benzene along with the hematological tests as markers of hematotoxicity.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene metabolism involves enzymes coded for by polymorphic genes.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Studies have shown that genotype at these loci may influence susceptibility to the toxic effects of benzene exposure.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Individuals carrying variant of NAD(P)H:quinone oxidoreductase 1 (NQO1), microsomal epoxide hydrolase (EPHX) and deletion of the glutathione S-transferase T1 (GSTT1) showed a greater frequency of DNA single-stranded breaks.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] One way of understanding the carcinogenic effects of benzene is by examining the products of biological oxidation.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Pure benzene, for example, oxidizes in the body to produce an epoxide, benzene oxide, which is not excreted readily and can interact with DNA to produce harmful mutations.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Outdoor air may contain low levels of benzene from automobile service stations, wood smoke, tobacco smoke, the transfer of gasoline, exhaust from motor vehicles, and industrial emissions.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] About 50% of the entire nationwide (United States) exposure to benzene results from smoking tobacco or from exposure to tobacco smoke.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] After smoking 32 cigarettes per day, the smoker would take in about 1.8 mg of benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] This amount is about 10 times the average daily intake of benzene by nonsmokers.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Inhaled benzene is primarily expelled unchanged through exhalation.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In a human study 16.4 to 41.6% of retained benzene was eliminated through the lungs within five to seven hours after a two- to three-hour exposure to 47 to 110 ppm and only 0.07 to 0.2% of the remaining benzene was excreted unchanged in the urine.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] After exposure to 63 to 405 mg/m3 of benzene for 1 to 5 hours, 51 to 87% was excreted in the urine as phenol over a period of 23 to 50 hours.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In another human study, 30% of absorbed dermally applied benzene, which is primarily metabolized in the liver, was excreted as phenol in the urine.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Under specific conditions and in the presence of other chemicals benzoic acid (a preservative) and ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) may interact to produce benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In March 2006, the official Food Standards Agency in United Kingdom conducted a survey of 150 brands of soft drinks.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] It found that four contained benzene levels above World Health Organization limits.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] The affected batches were removed from sale.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Similar problems were reported by the US Food & Drug Administration.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] In 2005, the water supply to the city of Harbin in China with a population of almost nine million people, was cut off because of a major benzene exposure.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Benzene leaked into the Songhua River, which supplies drinking water to the city, after an explosion at a China National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC) factory in the city of Jilin on 13 November 2005.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] When plastic water pipes are subject to high heat, the water may be contaminated with benzene.
[src:nanoputian/benzene] Nazi Germany used benzene administered via injection as one of their many methods for killing.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Construction of the structures depends on Sonogashira coupling and other synthetic techniques.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] By replacing the 1,3-dioxolane group with an appropriate ring structure, various other types of putians have been synthesized, e.g.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] NanoAthlete, NanoPilgrim, and NanoGreenBeret.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Placing thiol (R-SH) functional groups at the end of the legs enables them to "stand" on a gold surface.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] "NanoPutian" is a portmanteau of nanometer, a unit of length commonly used to measure chemical compounds, and lilliputian, a fictional race of humans in the novel Gulliver's Travels by Jonathan Swift.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] While there are no chemical or practical uses for the NanoKid molecule or any of its known derivatives outside of the classroom, James Tour has turned the NanoKid into a lifelike character to educate children in the sciences.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] To accomplish these goals, several video clips, CDs, as well as interactive computer programs were created.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Tour and his team invested over $250,000 into their project.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] In order to raise the funds for this endeavor, Tour used unrestricted funds from his professorship and small grants from Rice University, the Welch Foundation, the nanotech firm Zyvex, and Texas A&M University.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Tour also received $100,000 in 2002 from the Small Grants for Exploratory Research program, a division of the National Science Foundation.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] The main characters in the videos are animated versions of the NanoKid.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] They star in several videos and explain various scientific concepts, such as the periodic table, DNA, and covalent bonding.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Rice conducted several studies into the effectiveness of using the NanoKids materials.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] These studies found mostly positive results for the use of the NanoKids in the classroom.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] A 2004–2005 study in two schools districts in Ohio and Kentucky found that using NanoKids led to a 10–59% increase in understanding of the material presented.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Additionally, it was found that 82% of students found that NanoKids made learning science more interesting.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] To create the first NanoPutian, dubbed the NanoKid, 1,4-dibromobenzene was iodinated in sulfuric acid.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] To this product, “arms”, or 3,3-Dimethylbutyne, were then added through Sonogashira coupling.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Formylation of this structure was then achieved through using the organolithium reagent n-butyllithium followed by quenching with N,N-dimethylformamide (DMF) to create the aldehyde.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] 1,2-Ethanediol was added to this structure to protect the aldehyde using p-toluenesulfonic acid as a catalyst.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Originally, Chanteau and Tour aimed to couple this structure with alkynes, but this resulted in very low yields of the desired products.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] To remedy this, the bromide was replaced with iodide through lithium-halogen exchange and quenching by using 1,2-diiodoethane.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] This created the final structure of the upper body for the NanoKid.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] The synthesis of NanoPutian's lower body begins with nitroaniline as a starting material.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Addition of Br2 in acetic acid places two equivalents of bromine on the benzene ring.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] NH2 is an electron donating group, and NO2 is an electron withdrawing group, which both direct bromination to the meta position relative to the NO2 substituent.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Addition of NaNO2, H2SO4, and EtOH removes the NH2 substituent.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] The Lewis acid SnCl2, a reducing agent in THF/EtOH solvent, replaces NO2 with NH2, which is subsequently replaced by iodine upon the addition of NaNO2, H2SO4, and KI to yield 3,5-dibromoiodobenzene.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] In this step, the Sandmeyer reaction converts the primary amino group (NH2) to a diazonium leaving group (N2), which is subsequently replaced by iodine.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Iodine serves as an excellent coupling partner for the attachment of the stomach, which is executed through Sonogashira coupling with trimethylsilylacetylene to yield 3,5-dibromo(trimethylsilylethynyl)benzene.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Attachment of the legs replaces the Br substituents with 1-pentyne through another Sonogashira coupling to produce 3,5-(1′-Pentynyl)-1-(trimethylsilylethynyl) benzene.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] To complete the synthesis of the lower body, the TMS protecting group is removed by selective deprotection through the addition of K2CO3, MeOH, and CH2Cl2 to yield 3,5-(1′-Pentynyl)-1-ethynylbenzene.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] To attach the upper body of the NanoKid to the lower body, the two components were added to a solution of bis(triphenylphosphine)palladium(II) dichloride, copper(I) iodide, TEA, and THF.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] This resulted in the final structure of the NanoKid.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] NanoProfessionals have alternate molecular structures for the top of the head, and possibly include a hat.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Most can be synthesized from the NanoKid by an acetal exchange reaction with the desired 1,2- or 1,3- diol, using *p*-toluenesulfonic acid as catalyst and heated by microwave irradiation for a few minutes.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] The ultimate set of products was a recognizably diverse population of NanoPutians: NanoAthlete, NanoPilgrim, NanoGreenBeret, NanoJester, NanoMonarch, NanoTexan, NanoScholar, NanoBaker, and NanoChef.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] The majority of the figures are easily recognizable in their most stable conformation.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] A few have as their stable conformation a less recognizable shape, so these are often drawn in the more recognizable but less stable way.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Many liberties were taken in the visual depiction of the head dressings of the NanoPutians.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Some products are formed as a mixture of diastereomers—the configuration of the "neck" compared to parts of the "hat".
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] 3-Butyn-1-ol was reacted with methanesulfonyl chloride and triethanolamine to produce its mesylate.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] The mesylate was displaced to make thiolacetate.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] The thiol was coupled with 3,5-dibromo(trimethylsilylethynyl)benzene to create a free alkyne.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] The resulting product, 3,5-(4’-thiolacetyl-1’-butynyl)-1-(trimethylsilylethynyl)-benzene, had its trimethylsilyl group removed using tetra-n-butylammonium fluoride (TBAF) and AcOH/Ac2O in THF.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] The free alkyne was then coupled with the upper body product from the earlier synthesis.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] This resulted in a NanoKid with protected thiol feet.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] To make the NanoKid “stand’, the acetyl protecting groups were removed through the use of ammonium hydroxide in THF to create the free thiols.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] A gold-plated substrate was then dipped into the solution and incubated for four days.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Ellipsometry was used to determine the resulting thickness of the compound, and it was determined that the NanoKid was upright on the substrate.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Synthesis of the upper part of the NanoPutian chain begins with 1,3-dibromo-2,4-diiodobenzene as the starting material.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Sonogashira coupling with 4-oxytrimethylsilylbut-1-yne produces 2,5-bis(4-tert-butyldimethylsiloxy-1′-butynyl)-1,4-di-bromobenzene.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] One of the bromine substituents is converted to an aldehyde through an SN2 reaction with the strong base, n-BuLi, and THF in the aprotic polar solvent, DMF to produce 2,5-bis(4-tert-butyldimethylsiloxy-1′-butynyl)-4-bromobenzaldehyde.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Another Sonogashira coupling with 3,5-(1′-Pentynyl)-1-ethynylbenzene attaches the lower body of the NanoPutian.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] The conversion of the aldehyde group to a diether “head” occurs in two steps.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] The first step involves addition of ethylene glycol and trimethylsilyl chloride (TMSCl) in CH2Cl2 solvent.
[src:nanoputian/nanoputian] Addition of TBAF in THF solvent removes the silyl protecting group.
